	abstract = {{\textless}i{\textgreater}Context.{\textless}i/{\textgreater} While planet formation is thought to occur early in the history of a protoplanetary disk, the presence of planets embedded in disks, or of other processes driving disk evolution, might be traced from their imprints on the disk structure.{\textless}i{\textgreater}Aims.{\textless}i/{\textgreater} We study the morphology of the disk around the T Tauri star HD 143006, located in the {\textasciitilde}5–11 Myr-old Upper Sco region, and we look for signatures of the mechanisms driving its evolution.{\textless}i{\textgreater}Methods.{\textless}i/{\textgreater} We observed HD 143006 in polarized scattered light with VLT/SPHERE at near-infrared ({\textless}i{\textgreater}J{\textless}i/{\textgreater}-band, 1.2 {\textless}i{\textgreater}μ{\textless}i/{\textgreater}m) wavelengths, reaching an angular resolution of {\textasciitilde}0.037′′ ({\textasciitilde}6 au). We obtained two datasets, one with a 145 mas diameter coronagraph, and the other without, enabling us to probe the disk structure down to an angular separation of {\textasciitilde}0.06′′ ({\textasciitilde}10 au).{\textless}i{\textgreater}Results.{\textless}i/{\textgreater} In our observations, the disk of HD 143006 is clearly resolved up to {\textasciitilde}0.5′′ and shows a clear large-scale asymmetry with the eastern side brighter than the western side. We detect a number of additional features, including two gaps and a ring. The ring shows an overbrightness at a position angle (PA) of {\textasciitilde}140°, extending over a range in position angle of {\textasciitilde}60°, and two narrow dark regions. The two narrow dark lanes and the overall large-scale asymmetry are indicative of shadowing effects, likely due to a misaligned inner disk. We demonstrate the remarkable resemblance between the scattered light image of HD 143006 and a model prediction of a warped disk due to an inclined binary companion. The warped disk model, based on the hydrodynamic simulations combined with three-dimensional radiative transfer calculations, reproduces all major morphological features. However, it does not account for the observed overbrightness at PA {\textasciitilde} 140°.{\textless}i{\textgreater}Conclusions.{\textless}i/{\textgreater} Shadows have been detected in several protoplanetary disks, suggesting that misalignment in disks is not uncommon. However, the origin of the misalignment is not clear. As-yet-undetected stellar or massive planetary companions could be responsible for them, and naturally account for the presence of depleted inner cavities.},
